1
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:29,480
I owe everything to George
Bailey... Help him, dear Father.

2
00:01:29,520 --> 00:01:35,320
Joseph, Jesus and Mary.
Help my friend, Mr. Bailey.

3
00:01:35,680 --> 00:01:38,840
Help my son, George, tonight.

4
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:42,600
He never thinks about himself,
God, that's why he's in trouble.

5
00:01:42,680 --> 00:01:46,840
George is a good guy.
Give him a break, God...

6
00:01:46,880 --> 00:01:50,800
I love him, dear Lord.
Watch over him tonight...

7
00:01:50,880 --> 00:01:54,760
Please, God, something's
the matter with Daddy...

8
00:01:54,800 --> 00:01:59,320
Please bring Daddy back.

9
00:02:08,080 --> 00:02:10,000
Hello, Joseph. Trouble?

10
00:02:10,080 --> 00:02:12,720
Looks like we'll have
to send someone down.

11
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:16,440
A lot of people asking for help
for a man named George Bailey.

12
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:19,840
George Bailey. Yes. Tonight's
his crucial night. You're right.

13
00:02:19,880 --> 00:02:23,200
We'll have to send someone down
immediately. Whose turn is it?

14
00:02:23,240 --> 00:02:25,720
That's why I came to see you, sir.

15
00:02:25,760 --> 00:02:28,120
It's that clock-maker's turn again.

16
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:31,480
Oh, Clarence. Hasn't got
his wings yet, has he?

17
00:02:31,520 --> 00:02:33,600
We've passed him up right along.

18
00:02:33,640 --> 00:02:36,920
Because, you know, sir, he's
got the I.Q. Of a rabbit.

19
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:40,640
Yes, but he's got the
faith of a child. Simple.

20
00:02:40,680 --> 00:02:42,800
Joseph, send for Clarence.

21
00:02:46,200 --> 00:02:47,200
You sent for me, sir?

22
00:02:47,240 --> 00:02:50,520
Yes, Clarence. A man down
on earth needs our help.

23
00:02:50,560 --> 00:02:51,960
Splendid! Is he sick?

24
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,280
No. Worse. He's discouraged.

25
00:02:54,320 --> 00:02:57,200
At exactly ten forty-five
P.M., earth-time,

26
00:02:57,240 --> 00:03:01,080
that man will be thinking seriously
of throwing away God's greatest gift.

27
00:03:01,160 --> 00:03:05,160
Oh, dear, dear! His life! Then
I have only an hour to dress.

28
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:06,120
What are they wearing now?

29
00:03:06,200 --> 00:03:09,480
You will spend that hour getting
acquainted with George Bailey.

30
00:03:09,560 --> 00:03:16,040
Sir, lf I should accomplish this mission,
I mean, might I perhaps win my wings?

31
00:03:16,080 --> 00:03:18,560
I've been waiting for over
two hundred years now, sir...

32
00:03:18,600 --> 00:03:20,120
and people are beginniing to talk.

33
00:03:20,160 --> 00:03:22,120
What's that book you've got there?

34
00:03:22,160 --> 00:03:24,040
Oh, 'The Adventures of Tom Sawyer.'

35
00:03:24,080 --> 00:03:27,640
Clarence, you do a good job with
George Bailey and you'll get your wings.

36
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:29,720
Oh, thank you, sir. Thank you.

37
00:03:29,800 --> 00:03:31,880
Poor George. Sit down.

38
00:03:31,920 --> 00:03:33,880
Sit down?! What are we...

39
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:38,000
If you're going to help a man, you want
to know something about him, don't you?

40
00:03:38,040 --> 00:03:41,800
- Well, naturally, of course, I...
- Well, keep your eyes open.

41
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:45,640
- See the town?
- Where? I... I don't see a thing.

42
00:03:45,720 --> 00:03:48,720
Oh, I forgot. You haven't
got your wings yet.

43
00:03:48,760 --> 00:03:50,640
Now look, I'll help you out.

44
00:03:50,680 --> 00:03:52,400
Concentrate.

45
00:03:52,480 --> 00:03:54,720
Begin to see something?

46
00:03:54,760 --> 00:03:56,880
Why, yes! This is amazing!

47
00:03:56,960 --> 00:03:59,560
If you ever get your wings,
you'll see all by yourself.

48
00:03:59,640 --> 00:04:01,400
Oh, wonderful!

49
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:04,280
Yippee!

50
00:04:04,320 --> 00:04:06,880
Okay, boys, let's go.

51
00:04:06,960 --> 00:04:07,960
Hey, who's that?

52
00:04:08,040 --> 00:04:10,880
- That's your problem, George Bailey.
- A boy?!

53
00:04:10,960 --> 00:04:14,280
That's him when he was twelve.
Back in nineteen nineteen.

54
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:17,600
Something happens here you'll
have to remember later on.

55
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:24,520
Come on, Marty. Come on, Marty.

56
00:04:25,520 --> 00:04:29,600
- Hee-haw!
- Hee-haw!

57
00:04:29,640 --> 00:04:34,000
And here comes the scare-baby,
my kid brother, Harry Bailey!

58
00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:36,080
I'm not scared!

59
00:04:39,120 --> 00:04:45,040
Go, Harry! C'mon, Harry!
Attaboy, Harry! Come on, Harry!

60
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:49,400
Help, George! Help! Help!

61
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:52,120
...Harry, I'm coming!

62
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:54,600
- Help!
- Hang on, Harry!

63
00:04:54,680 --> 00:04:57,000
I'm coming! Chain Gang!

64
00:04:57,040 --> 00:05:00,120
George saved his
brother's life that day.

65
00:05:00,160 --> 00:05:03,800
But it caught him that cold
which infected his left ear.

66
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:06,160
Cost him his hearing in that ear.

67
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:09,880
It was weeks before he was able
to go back to his after-school job

68
00:05:09,920 --> 00:05:12,640
at old man Gower's Drugstore.

69
00:05:12,680 --> 00:05:14,000
Mr. Potter!

70
00:05:14,040 --> 00:05:16,240
Who's that? A king?

71
00:05:16,280 --> 00:05:18,360
That's Henry F. Potter.

72
00:05:18,400 --> 00:05:21,920
The richest and meanest
man in the county.

73
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:31,080
Hee-haw! Hee-haw!
Go to work, slave...

74
00:05:34,280 --> 00:05:39,360
I wish I had a million
dollars! Hot dog!

75
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:44,760
It's me, Mr. Gower. George Bailey.

76
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:46,920
- You're late
- Yes, sir.

77
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:58,960
Hello, George. Hello, Mary.

78
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:00,200
Hello, Violet.

79
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:01,760
Two-cents' worth of shoelaces?

80
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:03,480
She was here first.

81
00:06:03,560 --> 00:06:05,200
I'm still thinking.

82
00:06:05,240 --> 00:06:06,160
Shoelaces?

83
00:06:06,200 --> 00:06:09,840
Please, Georgie. I like him.

84
00:06:09,880 --> 00:06:11,720
You like every boy.

85
00:06:11,760 --> 00:06:13,560
What's wrong with that?

86
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:15,720
Here you are.

87
00:06:15,760 --> 00:06:18,480
- Help me down.
- Help you down?!

88
00:06:25,520 --> 00:06:27,360
Made up your mind yet?

89
00:06:27,400 --> 00:06:29,160
I'll take chocolate.

90
00:06:29,240 --> 00:06:30,360
With coconuts?

91
00:06:30,400 --> 00:06:32,280
I don't like coconuts.

92
00:06:32,320 --> 00:06:34,120
You don't like coconuts?

93
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:38,560
Say, brainless, don't you
know where coconuts come from?

94
00:06:38,600 --> 00:06:42,960
Look it here... from Tahiti,
Fiji Islands, the Coral Sea!

95
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:46,080
A new magazine! I never saw it before.

96
00:06:46,120 --> 00:06:47,320
Of course you never.

97
00:06:47,360 --> 00:06:49,360
Only us explorers can get it.

98
00:06:49,400 --> 00:06:54,480
I've been nominated for membership
in the National Geographic Society.

99
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:57,280
Is this the ear you can't hear on?

100
00:06:57,320 --> 00:07:00,520
George Bailey, I'll love
you till the day I die.

101
00:07:00,560 --> 00:07:03,680
I'm going out exploring
some day, you watch.

102
00:07:03,720 --> 00:07:07,280
And I'm gonna have a couple of
harems, and maybe three or four wives.

103
00:07:07,320 --> 00:07:08,640
Wait and see.

104
00:07:11,360 --> 00:07:14,480
- George! George!
- Yes, sir.

105
00:07:14,560 --> 00:07:17,640
You're not paid to be a canary.

106
00:07:17,680 --> 00:07:19,000
No, sir...

107
00:07:46,240 --> 00:07:48,360
Mr. Gower, do you want something?

108
00:07:48,400 --> 00:07:50,880
- Anything?
- No.

109
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:54,200
- Anything I can do back here?
- Nope.

110
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:55,560
I'll get them, sir.

111
00:07:55,600 --> 00:07:59,960
...take those capsules
over to Mrs. Blaine's.

112
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,080
- She's waiting for them.
- Yes, sir...

113
00:08:24,840 --> 00:08:27,280
They have the diphtheria
there, haven't they, sir?

114
00:08:27,320 --> 00:08:28,400
Ummm.

115
00:08:28,440 --> 00:08:30,280
Is it a charge, sir?

116
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:32,320
Yes, charge.

117
00:08:32,360 --> 00:08:34,920
- Mr. Gower, I think...
- Aw, get going!

118
00:08:34,960 --> 00:08:36,120
Yes, sir.

119
00:09:02,600 --> 00:09:04,560
Fast there, Captain
Cook! Where you headin'?

120
00:09:04,640 --> 00:09:05,800
Got to see Pop, Uncle Billy.

121
00:09:05,840 --> 00:09:07,800
- Some other time, George.
- It's important!

122
00:09:07,880 --> 00:09:10,560
There's a squall in there
that's shapin' up into a storm.

123
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:11,880
Uncle Billy, telephone.

124
00:09:11,920 --> 00:09:14,040
- Who is it?
- The Bank examiner.

125
00:09:14,120 --> 00:09:15,520
Bank examiner?

126
00:09:15,560 --> 00:09:17,760
Oh, I should have
called him yesterday.

127
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:19,320
Switch it inside.

128
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:22,760
I'm not crying, Mr. Potter.

129
00:09:22,800 --> 00:09:24,680
Well, you're begging and
that's a whole lot worse.

130
00:09:24,720 --> 00:09:26,760
All I'm asking for
is thirty days more.

131
00:09:26,800 --> 00:09:27,800
- Pop!
- Just a minute, son.

132
00:09:27,840 --> 00:09:30,720
Just thirty short days. I'll dig
up that five thousand somehow.

133
00:09:30,760 --> 00:09:32,360
- Shove me up. Shove me up.
- Pop!

134
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:36,640
Have you put any real pressure on these
people of yours to pay those mortgages?

135
00:09:36,720 --> 00:09:39,080
Times are bad, Mr. Potter. A lot
of these people are out of work.

136
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:40,800
- Then foreclose!
- I can't do that.

137
00:09:40,840 --> 00:09:42,440
- These families have children.
- Pop!

138
00:09:42,520 --> 00:09:43,600
They're not my children.

139
00:09:43,640 --> 00:09:45,920
But they're somebody's
children, Mr. Potter.

140
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:48,200
Are you running a
business or a charity ward?

141
00:09:48,240 --> 00:09:50,400
- Well, all right...
- Not with my money.

142
00:09:50,440 --> 00:09:53,080
Mr. Potter, what makes you
such a hard-skulled character?

143
00:09:53,120 --> 00:09:54,920
You have no family, no children.

144
00:09:54,960 --> 00:09:56,880
You can't begin to spend
all the money you've got.

145
00:09:56,960 --> 00:10:00,800
So I suppose I should give it
to miserable failures like you

146
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:03,520
and that idiot brother
of yours to spend for me.

147
00:10:03,560 --> 00:10:04,880
He's not a failure!

148
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:07,240
- You can't say that about my father!
- George, George, quiet. George...

149
00:10:07,320 --> 00:10:09,000
You're not! You're the
biggest man in town!

150
00:10:09,040 --> 00:10:10,120
- Run along.
- Bigger than him.

151
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:11,520
- Run along!
- Bigger than everybody!

152
00:10:11,560 --> 00:10:12,960
Gives you an idea of the Baileys.

153
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:14,880
Don't let him say things
like that about you, Pop.

154
00:10:14,920 --> 00:10:15,880
All right, son. All right.

155
00:10:15,920 --> 00:10:18,080
Thanks. I'll talk to you tonight.

156
00:10:25,520 --> 00:10:26,960
What!

157
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:30,720
Why, that medicine should
have been there an hour ago.

158
00:10:30,760 --> 00:10:33,520
It'll be over in five
minutes, Mrs. Blaine.

159
00:10:37,160 --> 00:10:39,520
Where's Mrs. Blaine's box of capsules?

160
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:41,320
I feel...

161
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:44,360
- Didn't you hear what I said?
- Yes, sir, I...

162
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:46,800
What kind of tricks
are you playing anyway?

163
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:50,960
Why didn't you deliver
them right away?

164
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:53,320
Don't you know that boy's very sick?

165
00:10:53,360 --> 00:10:55,000
You're hurting my sore ear.

166
00:10:55,080 --> 00:10:56,520
You lazy loafer!

167
00:10:56,560 --> 00:10:58,640
Mr. Gower, you don't
know what you're doing.

168
00:10:58,680 --> 00:11:00,680
You put something
wrong in those capsules.

169
00:11:00,720 --> 00:11:02,040
I know you're unhappy.

170
00:11:02,080 --> 00:11:03,880
You got that telegram
and you're upset.

171
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:05,680
You put something
bad in those capsules.

172
00:11:05,720 --> 00:11:07,560
It wasn't your fault, Mr. Gower.

173
00:11:09,280 --> 00:11:10,880
Just look and see what you did.

174
00:11:10,920 --> 00:11:12,440
Look at the bottle you
took the powder from.

175
00:11:12,480 --> 00:11:15,200
It's poison! I tell you it's poison!

176
00:11:15,240 --> 00:11:16,720
I know you feel bad.

177
00:11:16,760 --> 00:11:18,200
I didn't know...

178
00:11:22,240 --> 00:11:23,920
- Oh...
- Don't hurt my sore ear again.

179
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:25,320
- Don't hurt my sore ear again.
- Oh, no, no, no...

180
00:11:25,360 --> 00:11:28,320
Oh, George. George...

181
00:11:28,360 --> 00:11:31,120
Oh, Mr. Gower, I
won't ever tell anyone.

182
00:11:31,160 --> 00:11:32,600
I know what you're feeling.

183
00:11:32,680 --> 00:11:34,040
I won't tell a soul.

184
00:11:34,120 --> 00:11:37,280
- Hope to die, I won't.
- Oh, George, George...

185
00:11:37,320 --> 00:11:40,040
An overnight bag,
genuine English cowhide,

186
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:42,280
combination lock, fitted
up with brushes, combs...

187
00:11:42,320 --> 00:11:44,840
Nope! Nope, nope, nope, nope, nope.

188
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:47,480
Now look, Joe. Now look,

189
00:11:47,560 --> 00:11:49,440
I, l-I want a big one.

190
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:51,280
What did you stop it for?

191
00:11:51,320 --> 00:11:54,760
I want you to take a
good look at that face.

192
00:11:54,840 --> 00:11:56,760
- Who is it?
- George Bailey.

193
00:11:56,800 --> 00:12:00,080
Oh, you mean the kid that had his
ears slapped back by the druggist?

194
00:12:00,120 --> 00:12:01,680
That's the kid.

195
00:12:01,760 --> 00:12:04,400
Uh-huh. It's a good face.

196
00:12:04,440 --> 00:12:07,920
I like it. I like George Bailey.

197
00:12:07,960 --> 00:12:10,480
Tell me, did he ever tell
anyone about the pills?

198
00:12:10,520 --> 00:12:11,920
Not a soul.

199
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:14,800
Did he ever marry the girl?
Did he ever go exploring?

200
00:12:14,840 --> 00:12:17,280
Well, wait and see.

201
00:12:17,320 --> 00:12:19,440
Big... see... I, I don't
want one for one night.

202
00:12:19,480 --> 00:12:21,520
I want something for a
thousand and one nights.

203
00:12:21,560 --> 00:12:26,120
With plenty of room here for labels
from Italy and Baghdad, Samarkand...

204
00:12:26,160 --> 00:12:27,240
a great big one.

205
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:29,200
- I see, a flying carpet, huh?
- Yeah.

206
00:12:29,240 --> 00:12:32,080
I don't suppose you'd like this
old second-hand job, would you?

207
00:12:32,120 --> 00:12:33,320
Now you're talking.

208
00:12:33,360 --> 00:12:36,320
Gee whiz, I could use that as
a raft in case the boat sunk.

209
00:12:36,360 --> 00:12:39,240
- How much does this cost?
- No charge.

210
00:12:39,280 --> 00:12:41,600
That's my trick ear, Joe. It
sounded as if you said no charge.

211
00:12:41,640 --> 00:12:42,640
That's right.

212
00:12:43,800 --> 00:12:45,360
Well, what's my name doing on it here?

213
00:12:45,400 --> 00:12:48,240
A little present form old man Gower.
Came down and picked it out himself.

214
00:12:48,280 --> 00:12:49,200
He did?!

215
00:12:49,280 --> 00:12:52,200
What do you know about that...
my old boss. Isn't that nice?

216
00:12:52,240 --> 00:12:53,200
What boat you sailing on?

217
00:12:53,240 --> 00:12:55,240
I'm working across on a cattle boat.

218
00:12:55,280 --> 00:12:57,240
- A cattle boat?
- Okay, I like cows.

219
00:12:59,400 --> 00:13:01,080
- Hello, Mr. Gower.
- George!

220
00:13:01,120 --> 00:13:02,760
How are you? Thanks ever
so much for the baggage.

221
00:13:02,800 --> 00:13:04,360
- It's just exactly what I wanted.
- Aw, forget it.

222
00:13:04,400 --> 00:13:06,160
Oh, it's wonderful
of you to think of it.

223
00:13:06,200 --> 00:13:08,760
- Hope you enjoy it.
- Oh, oh, oh, oh.

224
00:13:08,800 --> 00:13:11,240
I wish I had a million
dollars. Hot dog!

225
00:13:11,280 --> 00:13:14,160
Avast there, Captain Cook!
You got your sealegs yet?

226
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:15,600
Parlez vous Francais, Mister?

227
00:13:15,640 --> 00:13:17,640
Hey, send us some of their picture
postcards, will you, George?

228
00:13:17,720 --> 00:13:19,520
Hey, George, don't take
any plugged nickels.

229
00:13:19,600 --> 00:13:21,560
Hey, George, your suitcase is leaking.

230
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:23,920
Hey, Ernie! Hi, Ernie!

231
00:13:23,960 --> 00:13:24,960
- Hiya, George.
- Hi, Bert.

232
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:27,040
- George...
- Hey, hey, I, I'm a rich tourist today.

233
00:13:27,120 --> 00:13:28,760
- How about driving me home in style?
- Great.

234
00:13:28,800 --> 00:13:32,120
Hop in Your Highness, hop in.
And for the carriage trade.

235
00:13:32,160 --> 00:13:33,720
I put on my hat.

236
00:13:35,720 --> 00:13:38,880
- Good afternoon, Mr. Bailey.
- Hello, Violet.

237
00:13:38,920 --> 00:13:41,080
Hey, you look good. That's
some dress you got on there.

238
00:13:41,120 --> 00:13:42,720
What! This old thing?

239
00:13:42,760 --> 00:13:45,080
Why, I only wear it when
I don't care how I look.

240
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:02,440
- How would you like...
- Yes.

241
00:14:04,520 --> 00:14:06,080
Want to come along, Bert?
We'll show you the town.

242
00:14:06,120 --> 00:14:10,360
No, thanks. I, uh, I've gotta go
home and see what the wife's doing.

243
00:14:12,520 --> 00:14:13,720
Family man.

244
00:14:15,320 --> 00:14:16,840
George! Harry!

245
