473
00:27:11,200 --> 00:27:14,680
Just say the word and I'll throw
a lasso around it and pull it down.

474
00:27:14,720 --> 00:27:17,040
Hey, that's a pretty good idea.

475
00:27:17,120 --> 00:27:22,000
- I'll give you the moon, Mary.
- I'll take it. Then what?

476
00:27:22,040 --> 00:27:23,680
Well then, you could swallow it,

477
00:27:23,760 --> 00:27:25,760
and it'd all dissolve, see?

478
00:27:25,800 --> 00:27:29,200
And the moon beams'd shoot out
of your fingers and your toes

479
00:27:29,240 --> 00:27:31,120
and the ends of your hair.

480
00:27:32,760 --> 00:27:34,120
Am I talking too much?

481
00:27:34,160 --> 00:27:35,400
Yes!

482
00:27:36,480 --> 00:27:38,720
Why don't you kiss her instead
of talking her to death?

483
00:27:38,760 --> 00:27:39,720
How's that?

484
00:27:39,760 --> 00:27:42,800
Why don't you kiss her instead
of talking her to death?

485
00:27:45,040 --> 00:27:46,240
Want me to kiss her, huh?

486
00:27:46,280 --> 00:27:51,040
Aw, youth is wasted
on the wrong people!

487
00:27:51,080 --> 00:27:54,400
Hey, hey, hold on. Hey,
mister, come on back out here.

488
00:27:54,440 --> 00:27:57,200
I'll show you some kissing
that'll put hair back on your head.

489
00:27:57,240 --> 00:27:58,520
What are you...

490
00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:07,360
Mary?

491
00:28:18,360 --> 00:28:21,080
Okay, I give up. Where are you?

492
00:28:21,120 --> 00:28:23,840
Over here, in the hydrangea bushes.

493
00:28:25,160 --> 00:28:27,240
Here you are. Catch.

494
00:28:27,280 --> 00:28:30,000
Wait a minute. What am I doing?

495
00:28:33,960 --> 00:28:37,040
This is a very interesting situation!

496
00:28:37,120 --> 00:28:40,120
- Please give me my robe.
- Hmm.

497
00:28:40,160 --> 00:28:42,880
A man doesn't get in a
situation like this every day.

498
00:28:42,960 --> 00:28:44,760
I'd like to have my robe.

499
00:28:44,840 --> 00:28:47,280
Not in Bedford Falls anyway.

500
00:28:47,320 --> 00:28:49,680
- Ooooouch! Oh!
- Gesundheit.

501
00:28:49,720 --> 00:28:51,680
- George Bailey!
- This requires a little thought here.

502
00:28:51,760 --> 00:28:53,440
Give me my robe!

503
00:28:53,480 --> 00:28:56,160
I've read about things
like this, but I never...

504
00:28:56,200 --> 00:28:59,120
Shame on you! I'm going
to tell your mother on you!

505
00:28:59,200 --> 00:29:02,040
Oh, my mother's way up
on the corner over there.

506
00:29:02,080 --> 00:29:03,800
I'll call the police!

507
00:29:03,880 --> 00:29:06,400
They're way downtown.
They'd be on my side, too.

508
00:29:06,480 --> 00:29:09,360
Then, then, then I'm going to scream!

509
00:29:09,400 --> 00:29:12,000
Maybe I could sell tickets.

510
00:29:12,040 --> 00:29:17,240
Let's see. No, no, the point
is, in order to get this robe...

511
00:29:17,280 --> 00:29:20,400
I've got it. I'll make
a deal with you, Mary.

512
00:29:20,440 --> 00:29:22,200
George! George!

513
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:26,880
George! Come on home. Quick.

514
00:29:26,920 --> 00:29:28,760
You father's had a stroke!

515
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:29,880
What?!

516
00:29:30,320 --> 00:29:32,040
Mary! Mary, I'm sorry. I've got to go.

517
00:29:32,080 --> 00:29:33,080
Come on, George. Let's hurry!

518
00:29:33,120 --> 00:29:35,720
- Did you get a doctor?
- Yes. Campbell's there now.

519
00:29:46,680 --> 00:29:49,520
I think that's all we'll need you for,
George, I know you're anxious to make a train.

520
00:29:49,560 --> 00:29:51,160
I have a taxi waiting downstairs.

521
00:29:51,200 --> 00:29:54,160
I want the Board to know that
George gave up his trip to Europe

522
00:29:54,240 --> 00:29:57,440
to help straighten things out
here these past few months.

523
00:29:57,520 --> 00:29:59,360
Good luck to you at school, George.

524
00:29:59,440 --> 00:30:01,200
- Thanks.
- Good luck! So long!

525
00:30:01,240 --> 00:30:03,760
Now we come to the real
purpose of this meeting...

526
00:30:03,800 --> 00:30:06,520
to appoint a successor to
our dear friend, Peter Bailey.

527
00:30:06,560 --> 00:30:08,760
Mr. Chairman, I'd like
to get to my real purpose.

528
00:30:08,840 --> 00:30:11,000
- Wait just a minute now.
- Wait for what?

529
00:30:11,040 --> 00:30:14,520
I claim this institution is
not necessary to this town.

530
00:30:14,560 --> 00:30:18,840
Therefore, Mr. Chairman, I make a
motion to dissolve this institution

531
00:30:18,880 --> 00:30:21,720
and turn its assets and
liabilities over to the receiver.

532
00:30:21,760 --> 00:30:23,200
Potter, you dirty, contemptible...

533
00:30:23,240 --> 00:30:24,440
I'll wring his neck,
so help me, George,

534
00:30:24,480 --> 00:30:26,040
- you hear what that buzzard...
- Mr. Chairman,

535
00:30:26,080 --> 00:30:30,560
it's too soon after Peter Bailey's death to
talk about chloroforming the Building and Loan.

536
00:30:30,600 --> 00:30:32,840
Peter Bailey died three months ago.

537
00:30:32,880 --> 00:30:34,680
I second Mr. Potter's motion.

538
00:30:34,720 --> 00:30:38,680
Very well. In that case, I'll ask the
two executive officers to withdraw.

539
00:30:38,760 --> 00:30:40,160
But before you go,

540
00:30:40,200 --> 00:30:42,920
I'm sure the whole Board wishes
to express its deep sorrow

541
00:30:42,960 --> 00:30:45,560
- at the passing of Peter Bailey.
- Thank you very much.

542
00:30:45,600 --> 00:30:49,280
It was his faith and devotion that
are responsible for this organization.

543
00:30:49,320 --> 00:30:51,200
I'll go further than that.

544
00:30:51,240 --> 00:30:55,880
I'll say that to the public, Peter
Bailey was the Building and Loan.

545
00:30:55,920 --> 00:30:58,080
Oh, that's fine,
Potter, coming from you,

546
00:30:58,160 --> 00:31:00,160
considering that you probably
drove him to his grave.

547
00:31:00,200 --> 00:31:03,120
Peter Bailey was not a business man.

548
00:31:03,160 --> 00:31:07,640
That's what killed him. Oh, I don't mean
any disrespect to him, God rest his soul.

549
00:31:07,680 --> 00:31:11,440
He was a man of high
ideals, so-called.

550
00:31:11,480 --> 00:31:15,440
But ideals without common
sense can ruin this town.

551
00:31:15,520 --> 00:31:19,360
Now, you take this loan
here to Ernie Bishop...

552
00:31:19,400 --> 00:31:25,360
you know, that fellow that sits around all
day on his brains in his taxi, you know.

553
00:31:25,440 --> 00:31:30,800
I happen to know the bank turned
down this loan, but he comes here

554
00:31:30,880 --> 00:31:36,480
and we're building him a house
worth five thousand dollars.

555
00:31:36,560 --> 00:31:38,920
- Why?
- Well, I handled that, Mr. Potter.

556
00:31:38,960 --> 00:31:40,160
You have all the papers there.

557
00:31:40,200 --> 00:31:43,200
His salary, insurance. I can
personally vouch for his character.

558
00:31:43,240 --> 00:31:45,800
- A friend of yours.
- Yes, sir.

559
00:31:45,880 --> 00:31:49,440
You see, if you shoot pool
with some employee here,

560
00:31:49,480 --> 00:31:52,080
you can come and borrow money.

561
00:31:52,120 --> 00:31:53,840
What does that get us?

562
00:31:53,880 --> 00:31:59,080
A discontented, lazy rabble
instead of a thrifty working class.

563
00:31:59,120 --> 00:32:04,240
And all because a few starry-eyed
dreamers like Peter Bailey

564
00:32:04,320 --> 00:32:08,520
stir them up and fill their heads
with a lot of impossible ideas.

565
00:32:08,560 --> 00:32:11,000
- Now, I say...
- Just a minute. Just a...

566
00:32:11,040 --> 00:32:13,400
Just a minute. Now,
hold on, Mr. Potter.

567
00:32:13,480 --> 00:32:16,640
You're right when you say my father
was no business man. I know that.

568
00:32:16,680 --> 00:32:20,000
Why he ever started this cheap penny-ante
Building and Loan, I'll never know.

569
00:32:20,040 --> 00:32:23,400
But neither you nor anybody else can
say anything against his character,

570
00:32:23,440 --> 00:32:25,320
because his whole life was...

571
00:32:25,360 --> 00:32:28,080
Why, in the twenty-five years since
he and Uncle Billy started this thing,

572
00:32:28,120 --> 00:32:30,760
he never once thought of himself.
Isn't that right, Uncle Billy?

573
00:32:30,800 --> 00:32:33,520
He didn't save enough money to
send Harry to school, let alone me.

574
00:32:33,560 --> 00:32:36,200
But he did help a few people get
out of your slums, Mr. Potter.

575
00:32:36,240 --> 00:32:37,440
And what's wrong with that?

576
00:32:37,520 --> 00:32:40,160
Why... here, you are
all businessmen here.

577
00:32:40,200 --> 00:32:43,360
Doesn't it make them better citizens?
Doesn't it make them better customers?

578
00:32:43,400 --> 00:32:45,360
You... you said that uh... what'd
you say just a minute ago...

579
00:32:45,400 --> 00:32:49,320
They, they had to wait and save their money
before they even thought of a decent home.

580
00:32:49,400 --> 00:32:51,200
Wait! Wait for what?

581
00:32:51,280 --> 00:32:52,720
Until their children
grow up and leave them?

582
00:32:52,760 --> 00:32:55,160
Until they're so old and
broken-down that they...

583
00:32:55,200 --> 00:32:58,280
Do you know how long it takes a working
man to save five thousand dollars?

584
00:32:58,360 --> 00:33:01,320
Just remember this, Mr. Potter, that
this rabble you're talking about...

585
00:33:01,400 --> 00:33:05,480
they do most of the working and paying
and living and dying in this community.

586
00:33:05,520 --> 00:33:07,720
Well, it is too much to have
them work and pay and live and die

587
00:33:07,760 --> 00:33:09,760
in a couple of decent
rooms and a bath?

588
00:33:09,800 --> 00:33:11,960
Anyway, my father didn't think so.

589
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:14,040
People were human beings to him,

590
00:33:14,120 --> 00:33:17,960
but to you, a warped, frustrated
old man, they're cattle.

591
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:20,480
Well, in my book, he died a much
richer man than you'll ever be.

592
00:33:20,520 --> 00:33:24,880
I'm not interested in your book. I'm
talking about the Building and Loan.

593
00:33:24,920 --> 00:33:26,680
I know very well what
you're talking about.

594
00:33:26,720 --> 00:33:30,040
You're talking about something you can't
get your fingers on, and it's galling you.

595
00:33:30,080 --> 00:33:32,480
That's what you're
talking about, I know.

596
00:33:32,560 --> 00:33:34,280
Well, I, I, I've said too much.

597
00:33:34,320 --> 00:33:38,000
I... You're, you're the Board here.
You do what you want with this thing.

598
00:33:38,040 --> 00:33:39,440
There's j-just one thing more though.

599
00:33:39,480 --> 00:33:42,600
This town needs this
measly one-horse institution

600
00:33:42,640 --> 00:33:46,600
if only to have some place where people
can come without crawling to Potter.

601
00:33:46,640 --> 00:33:47,840
Come on, Uncle Billy.

602
00:33:53,400 --> 00:33:58,880
Sentimental hogwash. I want my motion.

603
00:33:58,920 --> 00:34:01,120
Oh boy, that was telling
him, George, old boy.

604
00:34:01,200 --> 00:34:03,320
You shut his big mouth.
You should have heard him.

605
00:34:03,400 --> 00:34:04,480
What happened? We
heard a lot of yelling.

606
00:34:04,560 --> 00:34:08,000
Well, we're being voted out of
business after twenty-five years.

607
00:34:08,040 --> 00:34:09,400
Easy come, easy go.

608
00:34:09,440 --> 00:34:11,520
Here it is. "Help wanted
- Female."

609
00:34:11,560 --> 00:34:13,560
You still want me hang around, George?

610
00:34:13,600 --> 00:34:14,800
Yeah, I'll be right down.

611
00:34:14,840 --> 00:34:15,960
Hey, you'll miss your train.

612
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:17,800
You're a week late for
school already. Go on.

613
00:34:17,880 --> 00:34:20,800
- What's going on in there?
- Oh, never mind. Don't worry about that.

614
00:34:20,840 --> 00:34:22,960
They're putting us out
of business. So what?

615
00:34:23,040 --> 00:34:25,120
I can get another job.
I'm only fifty-five.

616
00:34:25,160 --> 00:34:26,760
- Fifty-six.
- Go on, go on.

617
00:34:26,800 --> 00:34:30,040
Hey, look, you gave up your boat trip, now
you don't want to miss college, too, do you?

618
00:34:30,080 --> 00:34:31,160
George! George!

619
00:34:31,240 --> 00:34:33,640
They voted Potter down.
They want to keep it going.

620
00:34:35,120 --> 00:34:37,080
- Whoopee!
- You did it, George, you did it.

621
00:34:37,120 --> 00:34:38,960
But they got one condition,
only one condition.

622
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:40,760
- What's that?
- That's the best part of it.

623
00:34:40,800 --> 00:34:44,200
They've appointed George here as Executive
Secretary to take his father's place.

624
00:34:44,240 --> 00:34:45,440
Oh, no! But, Uncle Billy...

625
00:34:45,480 --> 00:34:47,320
You can keep him on. That's all right.

626
00:34:47,400 --> 00:34:49,160
As Secretary you can
hire anyone you like.

627
00:34:49,200 --> 00:34:51,120
Dr. Campbell, now let's
get this thing straight.

628
00:34:51,160 --> 00:34:52,600
I'm leaving. I'm leaving right now.

629
00:34:52,640 --> 00:34:54,400
I'm going to school.
This is my last chance.

630
00:34:54,440 --> 00:34:55,880
Uncle Billy here, he's your man.

631
00:34:55,920 --> 00:34:58,560
But, George, they'll vote
with Potter otherwise.

632
00:35:00,920 --> 00:35:03,280
I know, I know, he didn't go.

633
00:35:03,360 --> 00:35:04,320
That's right.

634
00:35:04,360 --> 00:35:08,960
Not only that, but he gave his school money
to his brother, Harry, and sent him to college.

635
00:35:09,040 --> 00:35:10,800
Harry became a football star.

636
00:35:10,840 --> 00:35:12,960
Made second team All-American.

637
00:35:13,040 --> 00:35:15,040
Yeah, but what happened to George?

638
00:35:15,120 --> 00:35:18,240
George got four years older,
waiting for Harry to come back

639
00:35:18,280 --> 00:35:19,960
and take over the Building and Loan.

640
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:22,720
Oh, there are plenty of jobs around
for somebody that likes to travel.

641
00:35:22,760 --> 00:35:23,840
Look at this. There...

642
00:35:23,920 --> 00:35:28,320
Venezuela oil fields
- Wanted. Man with construction experience.

643
00:35:28,360 --> 00:35:33,120
Here's the Yukon, oh, right here -
wanted - man with engineering experience.

644
00:35:33,960 --> 00:35:35,760
There she blows.

645
00:35:35,840 --> 00:35:38,240
You know what the three most
exciting sounds in the world are?

646
00:35:38,280 --> 00:35:40,640
- Uh-huh. - Breakfast is served,
lunch is served, dinner...

647
00:35:40,680 --> 00:35:42,200
No, no, no, no!

648
00:35:42,240 --> 00:35:45,840
- Anchor chains, plane motors,
and train whistles.  - Peanut?

649
00:35:45,880 --> 00:35:47,080
There's the Professor now.

650
00:35:47,160 --> 00:35:51,040
- Phil Beta Kappa Bailey! All-American. -
Old George Geographic Explorer Bailey.

651
00:35:51,120 --> 00:35:52,840
What? No husky dogs? No sled?

652
00:35:52,920 --> 00:35:54,320
Uncle Billy, you
haven't changed a bit.

653
00:35:54,360 --> 00:35:57,760
- Nobody ever changes here, you know that.
- Oh, am I glad to see you.

654
00:35:57,800 --> 00:35:59,920
- Say, where's mother?
- She's home, cooking the fatted calf.

655
00:35:59,960 --> 00:36:02,000
- Come on. Let's go.
- Oh, wait! Wait, wait, wait, wait a minute.

656
00:36:02,080 --> 00:36:05,000
George, Uncle Billy, I
want you to meet Ruth.

657
00:36:05,040 --> 00:36:06,320
- Hello.
- How do you do.

658
00:36:06,360 --> 00:36:09,160
- Ruth Dakin.
- Ruth Dakin Bailey, if you don't mind.

659
00:36:09,240 --> 00:36:10,200
Huh?

660
00:36:10,280 --> 00:36:13,760
Well, I wired you I had a surprise.
Here she is. Meet the wife.

661
00:36:13,840 --> 00:36:16,680
Well, what do you know
- wife.

662
00:36:17,720 --> 00:36:20,160
Well, how do you do. Congratulations.

663
00:36:20,200 --> 00:36:22,520
What am I doing? Congratulations!

664
00:36:22,600 --> 00:36:26,480
They're married... why
didn't you tell somebody?

665
00:36:26,520 --> 00:36:28,920
...Oh, I can't wait
to see Tilly's face.

666
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:31,280
- Did you really marry him?
- Why, yes...

667
00:36:31,360 --> 00:36:34,680
What's a pretty girl like you doing
marrying this two-headed brother of mine?

668
00:36:34,720 --> 00:36:36,320
Well, I tell you.
It's purely mercenary.

669
00:36:36,360 --> 00:36:37,560
My father offered him a job.

670
00:36:37,600 --> 00:36:42,240
Oh, he gets you and a job?
Well, Harry's cup runneth over.

671
00:36:42,320 --> 00:36:45,160
Uh, George, about that
job, Ruth spoke out of turn.

672
00:36:45,200 --> 00:36:46,880
I never said I'd take it.

673
00:36:46,920 --> 00:36:49,800
You've been holding the bag
here for four years, and...

674
00:36:49,840 --> 00:36:51,360
well, I won't let you down, George.

675
00:36:51,440 --> 00:36:53,680
I would like to... Oh, wait
a minute. I forgot the bags.

676
00:36:53,760 --> 00:36:54,800
I'll be right back.

677
00:36:55,680 --> 00:37:00,400
It was a surprise to me. This is the
new Mrs. Bailey, my nephew's wife.

678
00:37:00,480 --> 00:37:06,160
Old, old friends of the family.

679
00:37:06,200 --> 00:37:09,320
- Oh, of course, I've heard him speak of you.
- And I want you to tell you,

680
00:37:09,360 --> 00:37:15,880
we're going to give the biggest
party this town ever saw.

681
00:37:15,920 --> 00:37:17,760
Here, have some popcorn.

682
00:37:19,120 --> 00:37:21,600
George, George, George, that's
all Harry ever talks about.

683
00:37:21,640 --> 00:37:24,960
Uh, uh, uh, Ruth, uh, this,
uh, what about this job?

684
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:27,840
Oh, well, my father owns
a glass factory in Buffalo.

685
00:37:27,880 --> 00:37:30,680
He wants to get Harry started
in the research business.

686
00:37:30,760 --> 00:37:33,200
- Well, is it a good job?
- Oh, yes, very.

687
00:37:33,280 --> 00:37:36,640
- Not much money, but, uh, good future, you know.
- I know.

688
00:37:36,720 --> 00:37:38,600
Harry's a genius at research.

689
00:37:38,680 --> 00:37:41,840
- My father just fell in love with him.
- And you did, too.

690
00:37:56,960 --> 00:37:59,840
Oh boy, oh boy, oh boy, oh boy.

691
00:37:59,880 --> 00:38:03,960
I feel so good. I could
spit in Potter's eye.

692
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:06,840
I think I will. I think I will.

693
00:38:06,920 --> 00:38:09,120
What did you say? Huhh?

694
00:38:09,160 --> 00:38:11,240
Oh, maybe I'd better go home.

695
00:38:11,280 --> 00:38:13,280
Where's my hat? Where's my...

696
00:38:13,320 --> 00:38:16,920
Oh! Oh, thank you,
George, which is mine?

697
00:38:16,960 --> 00:38:20,240
- The middle one.
- Oh, thank you, George, old boy, old boy.

698
00:38:20,280 --> 00:38:24,040
Now, look, if you'll point me in the right
direction... would you do that, George?

699
00:38:24,120 --> 00:38:27,480
- Right down here.
- Oh... Old Building and Loan pal, huh...

700
00:38:27,520 --> 00:38:30,880
Now you just turn this way and
go right straight down there.

701
00:38:30,920 --> 00:38:32,120
That way, huh?

702
00:38:32,160 --> 00:38:37,000
My Wild Irish rose...

703
00:38:39,840 --> 00:38:43,120
I'm all right. I'm all
